no differently than
any other prisoner.

30
00:05:23,368 --> 00:05:24,426
Excuse me.

31
00:05:25,470 --> 00:05:28,769
I finagled some real coffee from
the Chief Justice's office.

32
00:05:31,977 --> 00:05:34,810
Elsie's the best scavenger
in the entire building.

33
00:05:35,981 --> 00:05:38,074
You shouldn't have
gone to such trouble.

34
00:05:38,149 --> 00:05:41,585
Coffee's no trouble. Now a set
of tyres, that's another story.

35
00:05:45,657 --> 00:05:47,682
I still can't believe he's gone.

36
00:05:49,995 --> 00:05:52,862
For me, it was like
losing a father. Truly.

37
00:05:54,633 --> 00:05:56,726
Whatever I have, whatever I am...

38
00:05:57,269 --> 00:05:58,827
it's because of Roosevelt.

39
00:05:59,471 --> 00:06:02,907
I was in London, seeing
Churchill, when the news came.

40
00:06:03,942 --> 00:06:05,909
With the end of the
war in sight, the

41
00:06:05,910 --> 00:06:07,878
President sent me
as his confidant...

42
00:06:07,946 --> 00:06:10,608
to discuss a rather
tricky subject.

43
00:06:11,750 --> 00:06:14,241
What to do with
captured Nazi leaders?

44
00:06:15,820 --> 00:06:17,720
What was Churchill's opinion?

45
00:06:17,822 --> 00:06:18,822
He said:

46
00:06:19,024 --> 00:06:22,516
"They should be summarily shot
for crimes against humanity."

47
00:06:24,896 --> 00:06:26,386
What's your opinion?

48
00:06:26,898 --> 00:06:30,231
If it's a crime for the Nazis to
shoot people without a trial...

49
00:06:30,302 --> 00:06:33,100
how could it be less so for
us to do the same thing?

50
00:06:33,171 --> 00:06:35,105
That's Truman's feeling, exactly.

51
00:06:35,407 --> 00:06:37,568
And Churchill now
shares that view.

52
00:06:37,809 --> 00:06:39,834
Surprisingly enough,
so does Stalin.

53
00:06:39,911 --> 00:06:42,072
You're talking about a
war crimes trial...

54
00:06:42,147 --> 00:06:43,899
which they attempted
after the last

55
00:06:43,900 --> 00:06:45,605
war, and it completely unravelled.

56
00:06:45,817 --> 00:06:47,375
Because it had no weight.

57
00:06:47,452 --> 00:06:49,583
This will be an
international tribunal,

58
00:06:49,584 --> 00:06:51,183
comprised of the four powers:

59
00:06:51,389 --> 00:06:53,584
America, England,
France and Russia.

60
00:06:53,925 --> 00:06:57,520
President Truman wants the best
prosecutor in the country.

61
00:06:58,096 --> 00:07:01,588
One with a reputation for
being tough, but impartial.

62
00:07:02,567 --> 00:07:03,932
He wants you, Bob.

63
00:07:08,173 --> 00:07:10,437
I haven't prosecuted
a case in years.

64
00:07:11,076 --> 00:07:13,296
Roosevelt chose you
for the Supreme Court

65
00:07:13,297 --> 00:07:15,570
because of your integrity
as a prosecutor.

66
00:07:16,414 --> 00:07:18,009
That's why Truman picked you for

67
00:07:18,010 --> 00:07:19,906
this. Because he
wants a fair trial.

68
00:07:19,985 --> 00:07:21,509
Not a legal lynching.

69
00:07:21,987 --> 00:07:23,545
I like it right here, Sam.

70
00:07:23,621 --> 00:07:25,748
This would mean I would
have to step down.

71
00:07:26,024 --> 00:07:28,054
A temporary leave
of absence. You'd

72
00:07:28,055 --> 00:07:30,085
be back in six
months, maybe seven.

73
00:07:30,662 --> 00:07:32,621
Is the President aware of the fact

74
00:07:32,622 --> 00:07:34,928
that I'm opposed to
the death penalty?

75
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:36,924
Yes. But he's not
concerned, because

76
00:07:36,925 --> 00:07:38,902
he knows you'll do
whatever is right.

77
00:07:39,404 --> 00:07:42,305
As you know, a fair trial
means an uncertain outcome.

78
00:07:42,374 --> 00:07:44,535
If we don't prove the
defendants' guilt...

79
00:07:44,609 --> 00:07:47,772
they'd walk, even if we could
smell the blood on their hands.

80
00:07:47,846 --> 00:07:50,004
Do the Allied powers
understand that?

81
00:07:50,005 --> 00:07:51,005
Truman does.

82
00:07:52,250 --> 00:07:54,810
You'll have a chance to
make it clear to them.

83
00:07:54,886 --> 00:07:57,377
The trial is yours to create, Bob.

84
00:07:57,489 --> 00:08:01,448
You get to set the rules, hire
the staff, find the setting.

85
00:08:02,127 --> 00:08:04,322
You even get to pick
the defendants.

86
00:08:08,033 --> 00:08:10,365
This trial could unravel, too...

87
00:08:11,503 --> 00:08:14,666
like the last attempt, if
it is poorly planned...

88
00:08:15,106 --> 00:08:18,166
if it is unsound,
legally or morally.

89
00:08:20,779 --> 00:08:25,341
Or it could establish a basis
for conduct among nations...

90
00:08:26,351 --> 00:08:29,286
that would alter history
for generations to come.

91
00:08:36,995 --> 00:08:38,986
The trial will be held in Germany.

92
00:08:39,064 --> 00:08:42,830
That's where the defendants
are, the evidence, witnesses.

93
00:08:43,301 --> 00:08:45,496
Are there any decent
hotels still standing?

94
00:08:45,570 --> 00:08:47,498
I don't relish the
idea of spending

95
00:08:47,499 --> 00:08:49,267
months in some dreary army base.

96
00:08:50,708 --> 00:08:52,869
You won't have to
worry about that.

97
00:08:53,378 --> 00:08:56,404
No wives allowed at Army's
request. Bad for morale.

98
00:08:56,481 --> 00:08:58,949
All those men over there
for years without their...

99
00:08:59,017 --> 00:09:00,780
You don't want me there, fine.

100
00:09:00,852 --> 00:09:03,343
I'll be downstairs,
whenever you're ready.

101
00:09:11,029 --> 00:09:13,657
Eighteen minus three.

102
00:09:14,199 --> 00:09:15,199
Fifteen.

103
00:09:18,470 --> 00:09:21,371
Fifteen plus seven.

104
00:09:23,041 --> 00:09:24,041
Twenty-two.

105
00:09:27,612 --> 00:09:30,137
Nine minus nine...

106
00:09:34,152 --> 00:09:37,144
Good morning, General Spaatz.

107
00:09:39,791 --> 00:09:43,022
I'm afraid I have to ask you to
get dressed and pack for travel.

108
00:09:43,094 --> 00:09:44,789
Where are you moving us?

109
00:09:45,864 --> 00:09:47,297
Only the Reichsmarschall.

110
00:09:48,199 --> 00:09:50,326
You're being transferred
to Bad Mondorf.

111
00:09:50,401 --> 00:09:52,499
Well, you know, it's
a very pleasant

112
00:09:52,500 --> 00:09:54,201
spa, but why must I go alone?

113
00:09:56,508 --> 00:09:59,944
Because that's where they're
rounding up German war criminals.

114
00:10:00,979 --> 00:10:01,979
No.

115
00:10:05,483 --> 00:10:06,483
No.

116
00:10:07,218 --> 00:10:08,742
I'm sorry about that.

117
00:10:09,320 --> 00:10:10,514
Get dressed, please.

118
00:10:12,090 --> 00:10:13,489
You must be brave.

119
00:10:15,059 --> 00:10:16,253
Very, very brave.

120
00:10:16,494 --> 00:10:18,359
Edda, you will?

121
00:10:33,645 --> 00:10:36,978
We know who you are, Mr
"Jew Butcher of Krakow."

122
00:10:37,048 --> 00:10:40,040
And we've seen the camps,
too. Nazi bastard.

123
00:10:44,022 --> 00:10:46,650
I must say that I was lucky
when the Arms Ministry...

124
00:10:46,724 --> 00:10:48,885
was destroyed in an
air raid in 1943.

125
00:10:48,960 --> 00:10:51,428
It rid me of useless paperwork
and pencil pushers.

126
00:10:53,131 --> 00:10:54,131
Sir.

127
00:10:54,299 --> 00:10:56,243
What do you think
was the single most

128
00:10:56,244 --> 00:10:58,292
effective thing you
did during the war?

129
00:10:58,536 --> 00:11:01,130
When Hitler appointed me his
Minister of Armaments...

130
00:11:01,206 --> 00:11:04,539
I threw out the military chiefs
and turned to the professionals.

131
00:11:04,609 --> 00:11:06,509
Industrialists and engineers.

132
00:11:08,079 --> 00:11:10,479
Then I borrowed the ideas
of Walter Rathenau...

133
00:11:10,548 --> 00:11:12,012
the great Jewish chief of the

134
00:11:12,013 --> 00:11:13,881
German economy
during the last war.

135
00:11:13,952 --> 00:11:15,749
Standardisation of parts...

136
00:11:16,254 --> 00:11:19,451
the division of labour, and the
maximum use of the assembly line.

137
00:11:20,425 --> 00:11:21,653
Thank you, Dr Speer.

138
00:11:21,726 --> 00:11:23,660
Gentlemen, we'll now
break for lunch.

139
00:11:27,632 --> 00:11:28,997
Dr Albert Speer.

140
00:11:30,201 --> 00:11:31,293
Obviously.

141
00:11:31,636 --> 00:11:34,264
You're under arrest
for major war crimes.

142
00:11:41,846 --> 00:11:44,747
Move aside. Pay attention.
The orders are in.

143
00:11:46,317 --> 00:11:49,514
Listen up. You'll all be taken to
different places of detention.

144
00:11:49,587 --> 00:11:52,021
The following prisoners
will go to Bad Mondorf...

145
00:11:52,090 --> 00:11:54,923
as defendants in future war
crimes trials. Step forward.

146
00:11:55,393 --> 00:11:57,327
Field Marshal Wilhelm Keitel.

147
00:11:57,729 --> 00:11:59,560
Grand Admiral Karl Dönitz.

148
00:11:59,764 --> 00:12:01,664
Colonel General Alfred Jodl.

149
00:12:02,166 --> 00:12:03,258
Follow me.

150
00:12:07,105 --> 00:12:09,194
I haven't left Washington
since the war.

151
00:12:09,195 --> 00:12:11,132
I couldn't even
remember how to pack.

152
00:12:11,209 --> 00:12:14,235
I was so worried about bringing
the things for the office.

153
00:12:14,312 --> 00:12:16,337
I forgot half the
things that I need.

154
00:12:16,414 --> 00:12:18,437
I've one set of
nylons for the entire

155
00:12:18,438 --> 00:12:20,248
time and they already have a run.

156
00:12:20,451 --> 00:12:23,716
I even traded ration coupons with
my friend so I could buy nylons.

157
00:12:23,788 --> 00:12:27,019
You are as jittery as a hen.
What is the matter with you?

158
00:12:29,460 --> 00:12:31,587
I've never been up in
an aeroplane before.

159
00:12:43,107 --> 00:12:44,836
- Good morning, Robert.
- John.

160
00:12:44,909 --> 00:12:46,035
- Bob.
- Tom.

161
00:12:46,844 --> 00:12:48,368
Robert, good morning.

162
00:12:48,446 --> 00:12:50,744
This is my chief
secretary, Elsie Douglas.

163
00:12:50,815 --> 00:12:53,682
Elsie, this is Tom Dodd,
who'll be Deputy Prosecutor.

164
00:12:53,985 --> 00:12:56,279
It's nice to finally
meet you, Miss Douglas.

165
00:12:56,280 --> 00:12:57,280
Pleasure.

166
00:12:57,281 --> 00:12:59,589
Colonel John Harlan Amen,
Head of Interrogations.

167
00:12:59,657 --> 00:13:00,657
Miss Douglas.

168
00:13:00,692 --> 00:13:02,458
Colonel Telford
Taylor, our liaison

169
00:13:02,459 --> 00:13:04,128
with the other prosecuting teams.

170
00:13:04,195 --> 00:13:05,662
- Pleasure.
- All mine.

171
00:13:05,863 --> 00:13:08,923
And Colonel Robert Storey,
Head of Documents Division.

172
00:13:09,000 --> 00:13:10,490
Pleased to meet you, madam.

173
00:13:10,568 --> 00:13:12,365
Now that we're all here, let's go.

174
00:13:42,033 --> 00:13:44,661
So who are we really
after? Military leaders?

175
00:13:44,736 --> 00:13:45,828
Political leaders?

176
00:13:45,903 --> 00:13:47,145
What about the bankers and

177
00:13:47,146 --> 00:13:48,963
industrialists who
funded the Nazis?

178
00:13:49,040 --> 00:13:50,848
What about the
soldiers and civilians

179
00:13:50,849 --> 00:13:52,373
who carried out the atrocities?

180
00:13:52,443 --> 00:13:54,411
We can't put the whole
country on trial.

181
00:13:54,479 --> 00:13:56,640
We need to suggest the
scope of the crimes.

182
00:13:56,714 --> 00:13:58,875
I want this trial to
be the first of many.

183
00:13:58,950 --> 00:14:01,851
How about choosing a symbolic
figurehead from each category?

184
00:14:01,919 --> 00:14:03,580
We cover the whole spectrum.

185
00:14:03,654 --> 00:14:05,740
That way no one group
gets off scot-free.

186
00:14:05,741 --> 00:14:06,741
Makes sense.

187
00:14:06,742 --> 00:14:10,927
If we win, we can keep prosecuting
Nazis till the cows come home.

188
00:14:10,995 --> 00:14:13,395
Remember, we may also fail
to win convictions...

189
00:14:13,464 --> 00:14:16,831
in which case, some or all of
the defendants could go free.

190
00:14:16,901 --> 00:14:19,836
I'm still wrestling with the
validity of this trial.

191
00:14:20,538 --> 00:14:23,735
Crimes committed during war
have never been called crimes.

192
00:14:24,275 --> 00:14:27,711
Let's focus on existing law. What
existing laws did the Nazis break?

193
00:14:27,779 --> 00:14:30,359
Well, they broke peace
and border treaties,

194
00:14:30,360 --> 00:14:32,648
certainly Geneva and
Hague Convention.

195
00:14:32,717 --> 00:14:33,717
Right.

196
00:14:33,718 --> 00:14:36,178
Every time they invaded a
country, they broke a law.

197
00:14:36,254 --> 00:14:39,690
My fear is that at the end of the
day, when all is said and done...

198
00:14:40,224 --> 00:14:42,439
this trial will be
perceived as nothing

199
00:14:42,440 --> 00:14:44,490
more than triumph
of superior might.

200
00:14:44,862 --> 00:14:47,490
The winners exacting
punishment on the losers.

201
00:14:48,132 --> 00:14:50,258
Our task is to make
sure that this is

202
00:14:50,259 --> 00:14:52,330
not the triumph of
superior might...

203
00:14:52,403 --> 00:14:54,825
but the triumph of
superior morality. We're

204
00:14:54,826 --> 00:14:56,863
in a very interesting
position here.

205
00:14:57,141 --> 00:15:00,338
We are in a position to fashion a
future in which aggressive war...

206
00:15:00,411 --> 00:15:02,811
will be dealt with as a crime.

207
00:15:03,781 --> 00:15:04,907
Here, here.

208
00:15:34,612 --> 00:15:35,772
Move it. Let's go.

209
00:15:35,847 --> 00:15:38,782
Over there. Line them over
there. Come on, let's go.

210
00:15:47,992 --> 00:15:48,992
Corporal.

211
00:15:49,794 --> 00:15:52,228
New arrivals, identify yourselves.

212
00:15:52,697 --> 00:15:56,133
- Fritz Sauckel, sir.
- Head of Labour Conscription.

213
00:15:56,267 --> 00:15:57,427
Former head.

214
00:15:57,502 --> 00:16:00,198
- Julius Streicher.
- Publisher of...

215
00:16:00,371 --> 00:16:02,339
- I can't pronounce it.
- Der Strümer.

216
00:16:02,406 --> 00:16:03,406
It's filth.

217
00:16:03,608 --> 00:16:06,372
You bankers are all Jews, you
think I don't know that?

218
00:16:06,444 --> 00:16:07,444
Shut up.

219
00:16:07,445 --> 00:16:09,106
Hjalmar Horace Greeley Schacht...

220
00:16:09,180 --> 00:16:11,028
formerly President
of the Reichsbank

221
00:16:11,029 --> 00:16:12,479
and Minister of the Economy.

222
00:16:12,550 --> 00:16:15,144
I do not understand why I
have been accused here.

223
00:16:15,219 --> 00:16:18,279
I'm your jailer, not your lawyer.
You'll get your day in court.

224
00:16:18,356 --> 00:16:19,516
Hans Fritzsche.

225
00:16:19,590 --> 00:16:22,889
Chief of Radio Operations in
the Nazi Propaganda Ministry.

226
00:16:24,562 --> 00:16:27,224
Rudolf Hess, former Deputy Führer.

227
00:16:27,431 --> 00:16:28,431
Hess.

228
00:16:28,733 --> 00:16:31,293
- You.
- Joachim von Ribbentrop.

229
00:16:33,170 --> 00:16:34,762
Nazi Foreign Minister.

230
00:16:35,706 --> 00:16:36,706
You.

231
00:16:36,774 --> 00:16:39,937
Colonel, this is Dr Robert Ley,
head of the German Labour Front.

232
00:16:40,011 --> 00:16:41,740
- You're Albert Speer.
- Yes, sir.

233
00:16:41,812 --> 00:16:42,921
What's wrong with him?

234
00:16:42,922 --> 00:16:44,679
His mind's not what it used to be.

235
00:16:44,749 --> 00:16:47,327
He's a drunk, it finally
caught up with him.

236
00:16:47,328 --> 00:16:48,480
I said, "Shut up."

237
00:16:49,186 --> 00:16:50,186
Colonel.

238
00:16:50,621 --> 00:16:52,849
This man, Streicher,
is a disgusting

239
00:16:52,850 --> 00:16:55,320
person. A pornographer
and a Jew-baiter.

240
00:16:55,760 --> 00:16:57,567
I do not wish to be
housed with him.

241
00:16:57,568 --> 00:16:58,820
We make no distinctions.

242
00:16:58,896 --> 00:16:59,896
Colonel.

243
00:17:00,598 --> 00:17:02,998
We respectfully
protest our arrest.

244
00:17:03,167 --> 00:17:05,692
We were only following
orders, nothing more.

245
00:17:06,137 --> 00:17:08,867
As a fellow soldier, surely
you must understand.

246
00:17:20,785 --> 00:17:22,776
Now you're no longer a soldier.

247
00:17:23,087 --> 00:17:25,248
You are all war criminals.

248
00:17:25,656 --> 00:17:27,453
All of you. Lock them up.

249
00:17:29,226 --> 00:17:30,659
Nazi bastards.

250
00:17:31,228 --> 00:17:32,695
Where's the guard?

251
00:17:46,110 --> 00:17:49,546
Reichsmarschall Hermann
Göring at your service, sir.

252
00:17:49,880 --> 00:17:53,247
You are in the United States
Army Stockade at Bad Mondorf.

253
00:17:56,454 --> 00:17:58,479
