507
00:33:06,496 --> 00:33:08,896
- Thanks for the ride, Fuchs.
- No problem.

508
00:33:10,166 --> 00:33:11,166
Robert.

509
00:33:11,902 --> 00:33:14,063
- Welcome back.
- It's nice to be back.

510
00:33:14,938 --> 00:33:17,065
It's really good to have you back.

511
00:33:18,808 --> 00:33:19,808
So...

512
00:33:20,911 --> 00:33:22,578
Quite a job you've done here.

513
00:33:22,579 --> 00:33:24,677
You should see the
inside. Come on.

514
00:33:36,726 --> 00:33:39,286
Excellent. Excellent
work, Captain...

515
00:33:39,362 --> 00:33:40,362
Kiley.

516
00:33:40,463 --> 00:33:42,761
Kiley. What's your
background, Kiley?

517
00:33:42,899 --> 00:33:45,527
A couple of architecture
classes. Never got a degree.

518
00:33:45,602 --> 00:33:46,864
Neither did I.

519
00:33:47,504 --> 00:33:48,869
Are you serious?

520
00:33:49,239 --> 00:33:51,605
You're a justice of
the Supreme Court.

521
00:33:51,775 --> 00:33:53,754
I practised law for
20 years with only a

522
00:33:53,755 --> 00:33:55,734
single year of law
school under my belt.

523
00:33:55,812 --> 00:33:57,404
Things were easier back then.

524
00:33:57,480 --> 00:33:59,367
You shouldn't give
away your secrets.

525
00:33:59,368 --> 00:34:00,972
I won't tell if you won't tell.

526
00:34:01,051 --> 00:34:04,418
How are we doing with the gizmos
for the simultaneous translation?

527
00:34:04,487 --> 00:34:06,634
IBM's inventing the
process as we go, sir.

528
00:34:06,635 --> 00:34:08,583
But we'll be ready
for you, I promise.

529
00:34:08,992 --> 00:34:10,254
I don't doubt that.

530
00:34:10,327 --> 00:34:11,419
Excuse me.

531
00:34:12,562 --> 00:34:14,496
Question is, "Will we be ready?"

532
00:34:14,931 --> 00:34:18,230
The whole team's waiting in our
office. They'll fill you in.

533
00:34:20,003 --> 00:34:21,061
I missed you.

534
00:34:23,139 --> 00:34:24,538
I missed you, too.

535
00:34:26,776 --> 00:34:29,176
When I was home, I couldn't
find a phone number.

536
00:34:29,245 --> 00:34:30,837
I couldn't find a document.

537
00:34:30,914 --> 00:34:33,508
Now you won't have
to worry about that.

538
00:34:35,051 --> 00:34:36,450
I'll take Göring.

539
00:34:36,853 --> 00:34:38,115
Should be fun.

540
00:34:38,822 --> 00:34:40,756
Tom, I'd like you to do Speer.

541
00:34:40,924 --> 00:34:42,016
My pleasure.

542
00:34:42,092 --> 00:34:45,528
I'd also like you to take
von Schirach and Funk.

543
00:34:45,629 --> 00:34:46,629
Good.

544
00:34:47,130 --> 00:34:49,314
Are the indictments
ready to be served?

545
00:34:49,315 --> 00:34:51,499
I say we hold off
till the last moment.

546
00:34:51,635 --> 00:34:53,665
As it is, we get to
treat them like POWs.

547
00:34:53,666 --> 00:34:55,503
We can interrogate
them all day long.

548
00:34:55,839 --> 00:34:58,865
Once indicted, they're entitled
to have their lawyers present.

549
00:34:58,942 --> 00:35:00,739
This is going to be a fair trial.

550
00:35:00,810 --> 00:35:02,914
Let's serve them as
soon as possible. Let

551
00:35:02,915 --> 00:35:04,769
the British deliver
the indictments.

552
00:35:04,848 --> 00:35:07,180
It's not right for us
to hog the whole show.

553
00:35:07,250 --> 00:35:10,083
- What if they want Nazi lawyers?
- Hell, no.

554
00:35:10,387 --> 00:35:12,377
What crazy example would that set?

555
00:35:12,378 --> 00:35:13,378
Free speech.

556
00:35:13,423 --> 00:35:15,357
For crying out loud, boys.

557
00:35:15,558 --> 00:35:18,550
Nazis defending Nazis. They ought
to be on trial themselves.

558
00:35:18,628 --> 00:35:19,652
We have to pay them?

559
00:35:19,729 --> 00:35:23,028
I wonder what these fellows would
do if the situation was reversed.

560
00:35:23,099 --> 00:35:25,727
We don't have to answer
that question in this room.

561
00:35:25,802 --> 00:35:27,984
The judges will be here
in one week. We'll

562
00:35:27,985 --> 00:35:29,863
let them decide.
Will you excuse me?

563
00:35:33,610 --> 00:35:35,771
This just arrived from Biddle.

564
00:35:36,312 --> 00:35:37,939
He's decided not to fly.

565
00:35:38,014 --> 00:35:40,227
He's coming over on
the Queen Elizabeth.

566
00:35:40,228 --> 00:35:41,848
He'll be here in three weeks.

567
00:35:48,024 --> 00:35:49,992
I'm a bit surprised at Biddle.

568
00:35:50,260 --> 00:35:52,854
I'd never seen a man so
hungry for approval.

569
00:35:53,663 --> 00:35:56,063
Well, yeah, but then
you approved him.

570
00:35:57,067 --> 00:35:59,331
I did learn a lesson
there, didn't I?

571
00:35:59,402 --> 00:36:01,427
And how I hate learning lessons.

572
00:36:05,575 --> 00:36:07,770
Don't you think this
is a bit excessive?

573
00:36:07,844 --> 00:36:09,937
I got it for a really good price.

574
00:36:17,087 --> 00:36:18,179
Thank you.

575
00:36:20,156 --> 00:36:23,523
Justice Jackson, meet Frau
Hassel and Herr Hassel.

576
00:36:23,827 --> 00:36:24,827
Willkommen.

577
00:36:26,930 --> 00:36:29,763
How do you do? I have lived
five years in America.

578
00:36:30,400 --> 00:36:33,369
Well, it's a pleasure to
meet you, Frau Hassel.

579
00:36:33,737 --> 00:36:35,102
Please, come in.

580
00:36:38,808 --> 00:36:40,503
Follow me, bitte.

581
00:36:41,444 --> 00:36:44,641
I will prepare dinner. Something
light, perhaps, at this hour.

582
00:36:44,714 --> 00:36:45,806
Thank you.

583
00:36:47,350 --> 00:36:50,979
"Light" means five pounds of lard
in the dumplings instead of six.

584
00:36:52,188 --> 00:36:53,678
Who owns this place?

585
00:36:54,324 --> 00:36:56,562
Some banker who no
longer owns a bank. I

586
00:36:56,563 --> 00:36:58,693
think we're his only
source of income.

587
00:36:58,762 --> 00:36:59,762
Come on.

588
00:37:03,633 --> 00:37:05,931
Thank you, Herr
Hassel. I'll do that.

589
00:37:07,203 --> 00:37:08,397
Thank you very much.

590
00:37:16,513 --> 00:37:18,105
So where is your room?

591
00:37:18,448 --> 00:37:19,608
Upstairs.

592
00:37:19,983 --> 00:37:22,713
It's a cute little
attic-apartment type thing.

593
00:37:22,852 --> 00:37:24,183
Is it all right?

594
00:37:24,254 --> 00:37:27,223
Well, it's nicer than what
I have in Washington, Bob.

595
00:37:27,657 --> 00:37:30,148
I haven't seen what you
have in Washington.

596
00:37:31,361 --> 00:37:33,955
Oh God, I am so bushed.

597
00:37:34,030 --> 00:37:36,828
Just hold on till dinner.
Would you like a drink?

598
00:37:37,100 --> 00:37:38,567
No, maybe later on.

599
00:37:40,303 --> 00:37:41,565
Don't do that.

600
00:37:42,939 --> 00:37:46,102
I've arranged a breakfast meeting
with the team tomorrow morning.

601
00:37:46,176 --> 00:37:47,234
Good.

602
00:37:47,310 --> 00:37:49,437
Just to go over some finer points.

603
00:37:52,215 --> 00:37:53,978
You sure pack well, Bob.

604
00:38:04,494 --> 00:38:05,494
Bob.

605
00:38:22,679 --> 00:38:23,679
Thanks.

606
00:38:31,888 --> 00:38:33,617
Start with this one.

607
00:38:33,890 --> 00:38:35,899
I hope I shan't
make a balls of it.

608
00:38:35,900 --> 00:38:38,122
You'll be just fine,
old chap. Open up.

609
00:38:45,668 --> 00:38:46,896
Good morning.

610
00:38:47,770 --> 00:38:49,135
I am Major Neave.

611
00:38:49,405 --> 00:38:51,219
I am the officer appointed by the

612
00:38:51,220 --> 00:38:53,364
International Military
Tribunal to...

613
00:38:53,610 --> 00:38:54,610
Wait.

614
00:38:55,612 --> 00:38:57,239
- You're British?
- I am.

615
00:38:57,847 --> 00:38:59,838
Finally, a civilised man.

616
00:39:01,618 --> 00:39:02,618
Neave.

617
00:39:04,888 --> 00:39:06,583
What is your given name?

618
00:39:07,056 --> 00:39:08,056
Airey.

619
00:39:09,359 --> 00:39:11,156
Major Airey Neave.

620
00:39:11,661 --> 00:39:13,629
I have heard this name before.

621
00:39:14,130 --> 00:39:15,893
Airey, like the wind.

622
00:39:17,634 --> 00:39:19,397
Why would I have heard this name?

623
00:39:20,603 --> 00:39:24,539
I was captured, tortured by the
Gestapo, and escaped twice.

624
00:39:24,641 --> 00:39:27,439
I see. Then you've
earned your given name.

625
00:39:28,211 --> 00:39:31,703
I am the officer appointed by the
International Military Tribunal...

626
00:39:31,781 --> 00:39:34,147
to serve upon you a copy
of the indictment...

627
00:39:34,450 --> 00:39:36,816
in which you are
named as defendant.

628
00:39:36,986 --> 00:39:39,887
I'm also here to advise you
as to your rights to counsel.

629
00:39:40,823 --> 00:39:42,290
I care nothing for lawyers.

630
00:39:43,459 --> 00:39:46,326
You can find one for me,
Major Airey of the wind.

631
00:39:47,497 --> 00:39:48,759
We're men of culture.

632
00:39:48,998 --> 00:39:50,625
We both know the truth.

633
00:39:50,800 --> 00:39:53,200
The victors will
always be the judges.

634
00:39:53,603 --> 00:39:55,867
The vanquished,
always the accused.

635
00:39:55,972 --> 00:39:56,972
Yes?

636
00:40:20,229 --> 00:40:21,355
Open it up.

637
00:40:24,734 --> 00:40:27,149
Until I've studied this,
I cannot speak to

638
00:40:27,150 --> 00:40:29,398
the accuracy of the
charges against me.

639
00:40:30,173 --> 00:40:33,609
But I acknowledge the necessity
of this trial and accept...

640
00:40:34,510 --> 00:40:35,807
my inclusion in it.

641
00:40:35,878 --> 00:40:38,244
How can you say that before
reading the charges?

642
00:40:38,314 --> 00:40:41,249
There's a common responsibility
for the crimes committed...

643
00:40:41,317 --> 00:40:44,445
in the name of the Third
Reich. No one is blameless.

644
00:40:45,088 --> 00:40:46,578
Apart from the victims.

645
00:40:46,656 --> 00:40:48,487
But we were just following orders.

646
00:40:48,558 --> 00:40:50,856
I know nothing about
crimes against humanity.

647
00:40:50,927 --> 00:40:52,792
- Here's a list of lawyers.
- Jews.

648
00:40:53,229 --> 00:40:54,628
They're all Jew names.

649
00:40:54,731 --> 00:40:57,131
I want to be defended by
a German naval officer.

650
00:40:57,200 --> 00:41:00,226
I was a lawyer myself,
full of ideals.

651
00:41:01,904 --> 00:41:04,065
Why don't you just shoot us now?

652
00:41:05,375 --> 00:41:07,468
Why don't you shoot us now?

653
00:41:51,687 --> 00:41:54,986
I want a guard posted at the
porthole of every cell.

654
00:41:55,825 --> 00:41:58,316
They are to be watched
around the clock.

655
00:42:01,631 --> 00:42:04,725
I will not have them
taking the easy way out.

656
00:42:15,478 --> 00:42:18,345
- I need to pick up a document.
- I'll meet you in the office.

657
00:42:24,053 --> 00:42:26,399
Find any directives on
Polish slave labour?

658
00:42:26,400 --> 00:42:27,400
Take your pick.

659
00:42:27,790 --> 00:42:30,418
There's something peculiar
about the German character.

660
00:42:30,493 --> 00:42:33,519
Makes them keep detailed
records of everything they do.

661
00:42:33,596 --> 00:42:35,063
It's downright perverse.

662
00:42:36,132 --> 00:42:39,898
The Nazis put into writing every
criminal thought they ever had...

663
00:42:40,002 --> 00:42:42,266
and every criminal
act they ever did.

664
00:42:43,139 --> 00:42:46,108
In this room is enough evidence
to hang half the country.

665
00:42:46,642 --> 00:42:49,270
I'll settle for 21
clean convictions.

666
00:42:58,588 --> 00:43:01,022
- Get what you need?
- More than.

667
00:43:02,692 --> 00:43:05,889
I've arranged all your random
notes for the opening statement...

668
00:43:05,995 --> 00:43:07,758
into something less random.

669
00:43:08,297 --> 00:43:12,256
Legal, Thematic, Anecdotal,
Precedent, Theory.

670
00:43:13,836 --> 00:43:15,360
You're really something.

671
00:43:16,706 --> 00:43:18,606
When you decide what, let me know.

672
00:43:22,745 --> 00:43:24,440
Oh, my God.

673
00:43:30,186 --> 00:43:32,484
I don't believe this.

674
00:43:48,037 --> 00:43:51,131
I've noticed that this case has
inspired the orator in you.

675
00:43:54,076 --> 00:43:59,309
I tried to capture a tone, a
mood, for the entire case.

676
00:44:02,485 --> 00:44:04,919
A melancholy grandeur,
if you will.

677
00:44:05,888 --> 00:44:08,083
Well, it's all here.

678
00:44:13,963 --> 00:44:15,123
You have a...

679
00:44:17,099 --> 00:44:18,498
something right here.

680
00:44:26,943 --> 00:44:29,411
We only have two days
to finish the speech.

681
00:44:30,713 --> 00:44:32,544
Maybe you should start dictating.

682
00:44:35,084 --> 00:44:36,084
Right.

683
00:44:56,038 --> 00:44:58,239
This simultaneous
translation business is

684
00:44:58,240 --> 00:45:00,441
like taking a room in
the Tower of Babel.

685
00:45:01,410 --> 00:45:04,846
I can assure you, whoever designed
those electronic earmuffs...

686
00:45:04,914 --> 00:45:06,381
Earphones, Sir Geoffrey.

687
00:45:06,682 --> 00:45:09,161
Earphones. Whoever
designed them did

688
00:45:09,162 --> 00:45:11,642
not try them over a
barrister's wig.

689
00:45:11,821 --> 00:45:14,221
Not to worry. On you,
they'll be most becoming.

690
00:45:14,924 --> 00:45:16,619
That'll change my style...

691
00:45:16,993 --> 00:45:18,324
Who's that over there?

692
00:45:19,228 --> 00:45:22,959
He's a psychologist. The army
transferred him here to consult...

693
00:45:23,032 --> 00:45:25,330
on the suicide risks
among the prisoners.

694
00:45:36,178 --> 00:45:38,373
I had arranged for a
flight to pick you up.

695
00:45:38,447 --> 00:45:40,506
You were meant to be
here two weeks ago.

696
00:45:40,583 --> 00:45:43,416
What happened? You developed
a craving for shuffleboard?

697
00:45:44,287 --> 00:45:46,812
I just I needed time
to get up to speed.

698
00:45:47,189 --> 00:45:48,816
I worked the whole way over.

699
00:45:49,125 --> 00:45:50,456
I'm fully prepared.

700
00:45:51,661 --> 00:45:54,095
Any of my colleagues here?
I'd like to meet them.

701
00:45:54,196 --> 00:45:57,131
Perhaps later on. I need to
talk to you about something.

702
00:45:58,567 --> 00:46:00,899
- You must take some vodka.
- No, thank you.

703
00:46:00,970 --> 00:46:04,030
- Try it. It makes it strong.
- I am content with the cognac.

704
00:46:05,141 --> 00:46:07,701
- We do it all the time in Russia.
- You can't mix it.

705
00:46:07,777 --> 00:46:10,245
- We do it in Russia all the time.
- Not in France.

706
00:46:10,546 --> 00:46:11,911
Thank you. Thank you.

707
00:46:14,483 --> 00:46:15,973
Look at this, Bob.

708
00:46:18,020 --> 00:46:19,578
It was a gift from my family.

709
00:46:20,289 --> 00:46:22,072
After the trial I
will donate this,

710
00:46:22,073 --> 00:46:24,055
along with my papers,
to my alma mater.

711
00:46:24,126 --> 00:46:26,424
- I think future generations...
- Francis...

712
00:46:27,496 --> 00:46:31,296
On the subject of who will serve
as President of the Court...

713
00:46:32,134 --> 00:46:34,967
the British are prepared
to support you, but...

714
00:46:36,404 --> 00:46:37,404
Yes?

715
00:46:37,406 --> 00:46:39,772
It's not in the best
interests of the trial.

716
00:46:40,443 --> 00:46:43,537
The Americans are far too
dominant in this thing already.

717
00:46:43,612 --> 00:46:45,944
The trial must be viewed
as a joint effort.

718
00:46:46,215 --> 00:46:48,139
I really do have the
qualifications.

719
00:46:48,140 --> 00:46:49,140
I know you do.

720
00:46:52,054 --> 00:46:53,316
If not me, then who?

721
00:46:53,556 --> 00:46:54,989
Sir Geoffrey Lawrence.

722
00:46:55,691 --> 00:46:58,091
The British share
our sensibilities.

723
00:46:58,260 --> 00:47:01,821
That's a lot better than having de
Vabres or, God knows, Nikitchenko.

724
00:47:02,398 --> 00:47:04,730
I think I can sell the
French on this idea too.

725
00:47:05,968 --> 00:47:10,064
Everyone back home assumes that
I will be head of the Court.

726
00:47:10,172 --> 00:47:13,869
Francis, your role here will
be of incredible importance.

727
00:47:15,244 --> 00:47:19,613
This is probably the last
appointment of my career, Bob.

728
00:47:19,749 --> 00:47:21,512
This is how I'm going out.

729
00:47:21,584 --> 00:47:25,884
With great honour. Francis,
you'll be capping your career...

730
00:47:26,322 --> 00:47:27,687
with great honour.

731
00:47:41,470 --> 00:47:43,438
Now that Ley's done himself in...

732
00:47:43,939 --> 00:47:46,339
who should we get to
replace him in the dock?

733
00:47:46,442 --> 00:47:49,934
It's not a Broadway show. We don't
just bring out an understudy.

734
00:47:50,012 --> 00:47:52,606
We've still got 21 left.
It's a good number.

735
00:47:52,882 --> 00:47:54,372
Boys, they are coming back.

736
00:47:57,353 --> 00:48:00,015
- Biddle doesn't look too happy.
- Can you blame him?

737
00:48:00,356 --> 00:48:03,120
Gentlemen, I'd like to introduce
Judge Francis Biddle.

738
00:48:03,259 --> 00:48:05,090
Hello, sir. Pleased to see you.

739
00:48:16,939 --> 00:48:18,304
Ladies and gentlemen.

740
00:48:19,141 --> 00:48:20,165
Please.

741
00:48:20,943 --> 00:48:23,878
A salute to my
colleagues in the law.

742
00:48:24,780 --> 00:48:26,518
How fortunate we are to be in a

743
00:48:26,519 --> 00:48:28,876
profession where we
may speak our minds.

744
00:48:29,852 --> 00:48:32,821
Not like diplomats who must
behave like dogs on a leash.

745
00:48:37,693 --> 00:48:39,786
To the law.

746
00:48:44,333 --> 00:48:46,858
I was wondering if you'd
care to dance with me?

747
00:48:48,137 --> 00:48:49,832
I'm not much of a dancer.

748
00:48:50,539 --> 00:48:53,030
Well, let's go
embarrass ourselves.

749
00:49:27,209 --> 00:49:30,235
It's my opinion head-shrinking
has no place in this man's army.

750
00:49:30,579 --> 00:49:32,547
But you've been assigned
to me, Captain,

751
00:49:32,548 --> 00:49:34,276
and I plan to make
full use of you.

752
00:49:34,350 --> 00:49:37,080
You'll help me stop losing
any more of my prisoners.

753
00:49:37,253 --> 00:49:39,448
From what I know of
your set-up here...

754
00:49:39,522 --> 00:49:42,389
I can say that you've created
the perfect suicide ward.

755
00:49:42,491 --> 00:49:44,015
What are you talking about?

756
00:49:44,093 --> 00:49:47,324
These men have nothing to do all
day but think about their faith.

757
00:49:47,463 --> 00:49:48,657
They should.

758
00:49:48,731 --> 00:49:50,426
To keep them alive and sane...

759
00:49:50,499 --> 00:49:53,161
they need to be occupied,
mentally and physically.

760
00:49:53,235 --> 00:49:55,396
- A small library, for instance.
- Library?

761
00:49:55,471 --> 00:49:57,632
Would make all the
difference in the world.

762
00:49:57,706 --> 00:49:59,196
So would an exercise yard.

763
00:49:59,341 --> 00:50:01,434
I had something quite
different in mind.

764
00:50:01,544 --> 00:50:03,205
Put you in their lives.

765
00:50:03,279 --> 00:50:05,543
Give them somebody to
talk to, open up with.

766
00:50:05,781 --> 00:50:07,578
They'll surely jump
at the chance...

767
00:50:07,650 --> 00:50:09,288
to jibber-jabber with somebody as

768
00:50:09,289 --> 00:50:11,177
bright and enthusiastic
as yourself.

769
00:50:11,287 --> 00:50:13,915
They'll tell you what they're
thinking and planning.

770
00:50:14,490 --> 00:50:16,856
You'll report everything
you hear to me.

771
00:50:17,358 --> 00:50:18,358
Colonel...

772
00:50:18,360 --> 00:50:20,794
I will not hear anything
about morals and ethics.

773
00:50:21,397 --> 00:50:23,888
These men are
prisoners. Criminals.

774
00:50:25,234 --> 00:50:26,326
Not patients.

775
00:50:27,202 --> 00:50:29,568
That's the deal, Captain.
Take it or leave it.

776
00:50:32,007 --> 00:50:34,032
The library and the
exercise yard, sir?

777
00:50:35,077 --> 00:50:36,237
You got it.

778
00:50:40,482 --> 00:50:44,384
This place is worse than I
expected. What a nightmare.

779
00:50:44,453 --> 00:50:46,314
Where do we pick up
our press passes?

780
00:50:46,315 --> 00:50:47,479
The Palace of Justice.

781
00:50:48,524 --> 00:50:51,015
What's the metal bar on
the front of the jeep do?

782
00:50:51,093 --> 00:50:54,324
It cuts the wires that Germans
string across the road at night.

783
00:50:54,396 --> 00:50:56,591
Several GI's have already
been decapitated.

784
00:50:56,665 --> 00:50:57,665
Lovely.

785
00:50:58,400 --> 00:51:01,426
Here we are, gentlemen. I'll
take your bags to the hotel.

786
00:51:01,670 --> 00:51:04,036
All right. Thanks a lot,
buddy. See you around.

787
00:51:05,140 --> 00:51:07,054
Have press credentials
ready to show.

788
00:51:07,055 --> 00:51:08,769
You will be given press passes...

789
00:51:09,111 --> 00:51:13,104
and transferred to assigned
lodging. Get in line, gentlemen.

790
00:51:14,617 --> 00:51:15,914
Check this out.

791
00:51:21,457 --> 00:51:23,118
Nice and tight, please.

792
00:51:47,249 --> 00:51:48,773
We better go sign in.

793
00:52:02,531 --> 00:52:05,004
Rudolf, you put it
on the wrong foot.

794
00:52:05,005 --> 00:52:06,005
What?

795
00:52:06,006 --> 00:52:07,094
The shoe.

796
00:52:08,037 --> 00:52:09,037
Na ja.

797
00:52:09,438 --> 00:52:11,235
Hess seems completely mad.

798
00:52:12,074 --> 00:52:14,508
It is an act. He is being clever.

799
00:52:14,843 --> 00:52:17,397
If he was so clever,
he wouldn't have spent

800
00:52:17,398 --> 00:52:19,837
the last four years
in an English prison.

801
00:52:28,123 --> 00:52:31,615
I turned my diaries over to
the Americans, voluntarily.

802
00:52:33,262 --> 00:52:37,096
That proves that I tried to resign
as Governor-General of Poland.

803
00:52:38,767 --> 00:52:41,827
I did not approve of the
persecution of the Jews.

804
00:52:43,172 --> 00:52:47,165
Anyone reading my diaries, they
will know what was in my heart.

805
00:52:48,310 --> 00:52:52,076
They will understand that those
things I wrote about the Jews...

806
00:52:52,815 --> 00:52:54,407
the orders I signed...

807
00:52:55,818 --> 00:52:57,445
they were not sincere.

808
00:52:59,855 --> 00:53:01,413
I believe you, Herr Frank.

809
00:53:04,593 --> 00:53:08,620
And yet, you did do those things.

810
00:53:10,232 --> 00:53:11,699
How do you explain it?

811
00:53:12,935 --> 00:53:15,426
I don't mean legally. I'm
not a lawyer or a judge.

812
00:53:16,472 --> 00:53:18,838
I mean, how do you
explain it to yourself?

813
00:53:24,079 --> 00:53:25,239
I don't know.

814
00:53:31,153 --> 00:53:33,053
It's as though I am two people.

815
00:53:35,357 --> 00:53:39,259
The Hans Frank you see here, and
Hans Frank, the Nazi leader.

816
00:53:41,330 --> 00:53:44,322
I wonder how that other Frank
could do those things.

817
00:53:46,101 --> 00:53:49,468
This Frank looks at
that Frank and says:

818
00:53:52,908 --> 00:53:54,375
"You are a terrible man."

819
00:53:55,310 --> 00:53:57,210
And what does that Frank say back?

820
00:53:57,412 --> 00:53:58,412
He says:

821
00:53:59,281 --> 00:54:01,340
"I just wanted to keep my job."

822
00:54:05,554 --> 00:54:07,044
Friends.

823
00:54:07,723 --> 00:54:11,056
When we begin this grotesque
farce tomorrow, my friends...

824
00:54:11,660 --> 00:54:14,493
never forget that we're
here for one reason.

825
00:54:14,863 --> 00:54:16,728
And one reason only.

826
00:54:17,666 --> 00:54:19,964
We lost the war.

827
00:54:21,570 --> 00:54:25,438
But someday, a grateful
German nation...

828
00:54:25,874 --> 00:54:28,274
will honour our legacy.

829
00:54:32,014 --> 00:54:33,038
Doctor.

830
00:54:34,383 --> 00:54:36,544
What do you have if
you have one German?

831
00:54:37,886 --> 00:54:39,444
You have a fine man.

832
00:54:39,955 --> 00:54:41,946
Two Germans, a Bund.

833
00:54:42,825 --> 00:54:45,851
Three Germans? A war.

834
00:54:48,897 --> 00:54:51,457
Are you really in such a
good mood, Herr Göring?

835
00:54:52,134 --> 00:54:54,068
Or is this your way
of handling fear?

836
00:54:58,874 --> 00:54:59,874
Fear?

837
00:55:00,976 --> 00:55:02,637
What do I have to be afraid of?

838
00:55:03,812 --> 00:55:06,838
I've ordered thousands of men
into battle knowing full well...

839
00:55:06,915 --> 00:55:08,542
that not many would return.

840
00:55:09,718 --> 00:55:11,668
Why should I, their
leader, tremble

841
00:55:11,669 --> 00:55:13,620
when called upon
to face the enemy?

842
00:55:15,023 --> 00:55:19,392
I know that I'm a condemned
man. That is of no consequence.

843
00:55:19,962 --> 00:55:22,499
There is still work
to be done. And,

844
00:55:22,500 --> 00:55:24,695
mark my words, it will be done.

845
00:55:28,637 --> 00:55:31,128
One Englishman? An idiot.

846
00:55:31,907 --> 00:55:33,875
Two Englishmen? A club.

847
00:55:34,476 --> 00:55:37,138
Three Englishmen, an empire.

848
00:55:46,989 --> 00:55:49,116
I spoke with the
translators today...

849
00:55:49,224 --> 00:55:51,692
to get a sense of the pace
you need to maintain.

850
00:55:51,760 --> 00:55:53,921
It's tricky. It's not
just about pace.

851
00:55:54,196 --> 00:55:57,029
It's about rhythm, pausing
at the end of phrases.

852
00:55:57,099 --> 00:55:58,964
We should rehearse
a little tonight.

853
00:55:59,067 --> 00:56:01,535
Not the whole speech. You
need to save your voice.

854
00:56:06,775 --> 00:56:08,834
This is unbelievable.

855
00:56:50,218 --> 00:56:51,549
Open them up.

856
00:56:55,490 --> 00:56:58,186
- Good morning, Leutnant Wheelis.
- Good morning, sir.

857
00:56:58,660 --> 00:57:00,423
It's time to go, Reichsmarschall.

858
00:57:02,597 --> 00:57:03,689
How do I look?

859
00:57:05,734 --> 00:57:08,760
You look fine, sir.
How do you feel?

860
00:57:08,870 --> 00:57:13,068
Excited. I have waited many
months. Many months of silence.

861
00:57:13,675 --> 00:57:15,472
Now at last I'm being heard.

862
00:57:18,780 --> 00:57:21,578
- Shall we?
- I'm not allowed to do that, sir.

863
00:57:21,817 --> 00:57:23,307
Yes, of course.

864
00:57:23,919 --> 00:57:25,113
Bring them out.

865
00:57:32,027 --> 00:57:33,221
Hitch them up.

866
00:57:40,869 --> 00:57:42,131
Pull them out.

867
00:57:49,411 --> 00:57:51,811
All right, Sergeant,
search the cells.

868
00:59:49,264 --> 00:59:50,390
Sir Geoffrey.

869
00:59:53,068 --> 00:59:54,399
With my respects.

870
00:59:57,272 --> 00:59:58,466
Bless you, Biddle.

871
01:00:01,076 --> 01:00:02,202
After you.

872
01:00:07,249 --> 01:00:08,511
All rise.

873
01:00:51,660 --> 01:00:54,754
This trial, which
is now to begin...

874
01:00:55,497 --> 01:00:58,489
is unique in the annals
of jurisprudence.

875
01:01:00,302 --> 01:01:02,720
The defendants, all
having been served

876
01:01:02,721 --> 01:01:04,830
with copies of the indictments...

877
01:01:05,273 --> 01:01:07,138
are now to enter their pleas.

878
01:01:09,477 --> 01:01:10,603
Hermann Göring.

879
01:01:11,179 --> 01:01:14,410
I have a statement which I
will now read to the court.

880
01:01:14,749 --> 01:01:17,411
The defendants are not
to make a speech.

881
01:01:17,652 --> 01:01:19,313
They are only to enter a plea.

882
01:01:21,489 --> 01:01:23,500
I declare myself,
in the sense of the

883
01:01:23,501 --> 01:01:25,619
indictment, nicht
schuldig. Not guilty.

884
01:01:25,994 --> 01:01:27,188
Rudolf Hess.

885
01:01:27,796 --> 01:01:29,229
Nein, nein.

886
01:01:29,931 --> 01:01:31,796
Record that as "not guilty."

887
01:01:33,902 --> 01:01:36,769
- Joachim von Ribbentrop.
- Nicht schuldig.

888
01:01:37,472 --> 01:01:39,963
- Wilhelm Keitel.
- Nicht schuldig.

889
01:01:40,709 --> 01:01:44,076
- Ernst Kaltenbrunner.
- Nicht schuldig.

890
01:01:44,746 --> 01:01:47,306
- Alfred Rosenberg.
- Nicht schuldig.

891
01:01:48,283 --> 01:01:51,275
- Hans Frank.
- Nicht schuldig.

892
01:01:51,753 --> 01:01:54,449
- Wilhelm Frick.
- Nicht schuldig.

893
01:01:54,789 --> 01:01:57,553
- Julius Streicher.
- Nicht schuldig.

894
01:01:57,926 --> 01:02:00,895
- Walther Funk.
- Nicht schuldig.

895
01:02:01,263 --> 01:02:04,027
- Hjalmar Schacht.
- Nicht schuldig.

896
01:02:04,299 --> 01:02:06,961
- Karl Dönitz.
- Nicht schuldig.

897
01:02:07,135 --> 01:02:09,831
- Erich Raeder.
- Nicht schuldig.

898
01:02:09,904 --> 01:02:12,202
- Baldur von Schirach.
- Nicht schuldig.

899
01:02:12,407 --> 01:02:14,671
- Fritz Sauckel.
- Nicht schuldig.

900
01:02:14,743 --> 01:02:16,711
- Alfred Jodl.
- Nicht schuldig.

901
01:02:16,811 --> 01:02:19,302
- Franz von Papen.
- Nicht schuldig.

902
01:02:19,381 --> 01:02:22,145
- Arthur Seyss-Inquart.
- Nicht schuldig.

903
01:02:22,417 --> 01:02:24,817
- Albert Speer.
- Nicht schuldig.

904
01:02:25,020 --> 01:02:27,420
- Konstantin van Neurath.
- Nicht schuldig.

905
01:02:28,523 --> 01:02:31,014
- And Hans Fritzsche.
- Nicht schuldig.

906
01:02:33,028 --> 01:02:35,394
All the pleas have
now been entered.

907
01:02:36,464 --> 01:02:37,556
Justice Jackson.

908
01:02:38,133 --> 01:02:40,124
Your opening address, please.

909
01:02:49,411 --> 01:02:51,072
May it please your honours.

910
01:02:52,247 --> 01:02:55,045
The privilege of opening the
first trial in history...

911
01:02:55,116 --> 01:02:57,914
for crimes against the
peace of the world...

912
01:02:58,553 --> 01:03:00,487
imposes a grave responsibility.

913
01:03:02,324 --> 01:03:04,482
The wrongs which
we seek to condemn

914
01:03:04,483 --> 01:03:06,761
and punish have been
so calculated...

915
01:03:06,828 --> 01:03:09,228
so malignant, and
so devastating...

916
01:03:09,898 --> 01:03:12,765
that civilisation cannot
tolerate their being ignored...

917
01:03:12,834 --> 01:03:15,701
because it cannot survive
their being repeated.

918
01:03:18,206 --> 01:03:20,488
That four great
nations, flushed with

919
01:03:20,489 --> 01:03:22,472
victory and stung with injury...

920
01:03:22,744 --> 01:03:25,013
stay the hand of vengeance
and voluntarily

921
01:03:25,014 --> 01:03:26,703
submit their captive enemies...

922
01:03:26,781 --> 01:03:28,578
to the judgement of the law...

923
01:03:29,250 --> 01:03:31,351
is one of the most
significant tributes

924
01:03:31,352 --> 01:03:33,243
that Power has ever
paid to Reason.

925
01:03:34,656 --> 01:03:37,317
If these men are the
first war leaders

926
01:03:37,318 --> 01:03:40,117
of a defeated nation
to be prosecuted...

927
01:03:40,662 --> 01:03:42,687
in the name of the law...

928
01:03:43,331 --> 01:03:47,233
we agree that here they must be
given a presumption of innocence.

929
01:03:47,936 --> 01:03:50,063
We accept the burden...

930
01:03:51,005 --> 01:03:53,269
of proving criminal acts...

931
01:03:53,641 --> 01:03:55,541
and the responsibility...

932
01:03:55,944 --> 01:03:59,778
of these defendants
for their commission.

933
01:04:02,083 --> 01:04:03,914
We have no purpose here...

934
01:04:04,419 --> 01:04:06,819
to incriminate the
whole German people.

935
01:04:08,690 --> 01:04:12,182
Hitler did not achieve power by
majority vote, but seized it...

936
01:04:12,827 --> 01:04:15,887
by an evil alliance
of revolutionists...

937
01:04:16,731 --> 01:04:18,198
reactionaries...

938
01:04:18,867 --> 01:04:20,266
and militarists.

939
01:04:20,969 --> 01:04:23,274
You will hear today
and in the days

940
01:04:23,275 --> 01:04:25,838
ahead of the enormity
and the horror...

941
01:04:26,207 --> 01:04:27,640
of their acts.

942
01:04:28,376 --> 01:04:31,072
The prosecution will give
you undeniable proofs...

943
01:04:31,780 --> 01:04:33,577
of these incredible events.

944
01:04:34,048 --> 01:04:36,863
I count myself as one
who received, during

945
01:04:36,864 --> 01:04:39,680
this war, atrocity tales
with suspicion...

946
01:04:40,822 --> 01:04:43,655
or scepticism. No more.

947
01:04:45,860 --> 01:04:49,626
The catalogue of crimes will omit
nothing that could be conceived...

948
01:04:49,697 --> 01:04:53,929
by their pathological pride,
cruelty, and lust for power.

949
01:04:55,937 --> 01:04:58,633
You will hear of the repression
of organised labour.

950
01:04:59,207 --> 01:05:02,506
The harassment of the Church,
the persecution of the Jews.

951
01:05:02,577 --> 01:05:04,835
The conversion of
mere anti-Semitism

952
01:05:04,836 --> 01:05:06,240
into the deliberate...

953
01:05:06,314 --> 01:05:09,477
extermination of the
Jews of Europe.

954
01:05:10,952 --> 01:05:13,648
You'll hear of the long series
of German aggressions...

955
01:05:13,721 --> 01:05:16,417
and conquests and broken treaties.

956
01:05:16,858 --> 01:05:19,156
The terror that
settled over Germany.

957
01:05:19,394 --> 01:05:22,329
The havoc wrought on the
occupied territories.

958
01:05:22,497 --> 01:05:26,207
And you'll know that
the real complaining

959
01:05:26,208 --> 01:05:29,300
party at your bar is Civilisation.

960
01:05:30,505 --> 01:05:33,018
Civilisation asks
whether law is so

961
01:05:33,019 --> 01:05:35,602
laggard as to be
utterly helpless...

962
01:05:35,877 --> 01:05:38,641
to deal with crimes
of this magnitude...

963
01:05:39,013 --> 01:05:42,847
by criminals of this
order of importance.

964
01:05:45,153 --> 01:05:49,988
It does not expect that you
can make war impossible.

965
01:05:51,259 --> 01:05:53,814
It does expect that
your juridical action

966
01:05:53,815 --> 01:05:56,492
will put the forces of
international law...

967
01:05:59,067 --> 01:06:05,028
its precepts, its prohibitions
and, above all, its sanctions...

968
01:06:07,342 --> 01:06:08,741
on the side of peace.

969
01:06:10,545 --> 01:06:14,606
So that men and women of good
will in all countries...

970
01:06:15,917 --> 01:06:23,085
may have leave to live by no
man's leave, underneath the law.

971
01:06:32,667 --> 01:06:34,760
The court is now adjourned.

972
01:06:49,017 --> 01:06:51,703
Jackson's speech?
Pedantic. Tiresome

973
01:06:51,704 --> 01:06:54,319
lot of nothing. I
nodded off twice.

974
01:06:54,522 --> 01:06:56,418
The food is better
today. Do you think

975
01:06:56,419 --> 01:06:58,219
they'll feed us like
this every day?

976
01:06:58,293 --> 01:07:00,761
They always feed you well
before they hang you.

977
01:07:00,828 --> 01:07:01,852
That's so true.

978
01:07:01,930 --> 01:07:06,264
They can't hang us. We're
soldiers. They have to shoot us.

979
01:07:07,569 --> 01:07:11,596
Stop this talk. We must
concentrate on our defence.

980
01:07:16,444 --> 01:07:20,175
If you are not going to
eat, Frank, give it to me.

981
01:07:20,615 --> 01:07:23,106
It's a crime to waste
such good food.

982
01:07:25,987 --> 01:07:28,649
Look what they have done
to your beautiful city.

983
01:07:28,756 --> 01:07:31,054
- Nuremberg is not mine.
- But it was.

984
01:07:31,292 --> 01:07:33,536
Was anything ever more
extraordinary than

985
01:07:33,537 --> 01:07:35,729
the Parteitagen you
staged in September?

986
01:07:36,631 --> 01:07:38,785
The night skies lit up
like a bonfire as we

987
01:07:38,786 --> 01:07:40,795
carried our torches
through the streets.

988
01:07:40,868 --> 01:07:43,962
A quarter million of us on our
way to the Zeppelin Fields.

989
01:07:44,372 --> 01:07:46,559
I remember standing
there for hours,

990
01:07:46,560 --> 01:07:48,866
basking in the radiance
of the Führer.

991
01:07:50,845 --> 01:07:53,837
Then I would take a group of my
Hitlerjugend to the river...

992
01:07:53,915 --> 01:07:55,746
where we'd would bathe together.

993
01:07:57,518 --> 01:08:00,817
We'd cool off from the fires
that were burning within us.

994
01:08:03,691 --> 01:08:05,818
But now that just
seems like a dream.

995
01:08:06,494 --> 01:08:10,487
A strange, wonderful,
frightening dream.

996
01:08:10,932 --> 01:08:13,230
It was not a dream,
it was a nightmare...

997
01:08:14,002 --> 01:08:16,664
of our own making. And it's
time to wake up from it.

998
01:08:17,071 --> 01:08:20,768
The look in Hitler's eyes was
not radiance, it was madness.

999
01:08:28,182 --> 01:08:30,309
Is the British prosecution ready?

1000
01:08:30,385 --> 01:08:32,444
Yes. Indeed we are.

1001
01:08:33,488 --> 01:08:35,278
Your Honours, with
permission I wish

1002
01:08:35,279 --> 01:08:36,924
to read from a sworn affidavit...

1003
01:08:36,991 --> 01:08:39,585
by one Hermann Friedrich Graebe.

1004
01:08:39,727 --> 01:08:43,629
A German construction manager
who, in a civilian capacity...

1005
01:08:43,698 --> 01:08:46,170
was employed by the German Army in

1006
01:08:46,171 --> 01:08:48,863
occupied Ukraine
